**user**:
> How do I specify in javascript that I want a globally defined variable to be set, not a new variable created?
**assistant**:
> In JavaScript, to ensure you are modifying a globally defined variable rather than creating a new one, you should avoid using the `var`, `let`, or `const` keywords when setting the variable if it is already defined globally. Instead, directly assign a new value to the variable.
> 
> Here's an example:
> 
> ```javascript
> // Assume this is a globally defined variable
> var globalVariable = 10;
> 
> function modifyGlobalVariable(newValue) {
>     // Directly assign a new value to the globally defined variable
>     globalVariable = newValue;
> }
> 
> modifyGlobalVariable(20);
> console.log(globalVariable);  // Outputs: 20
> ```
> 
> Key points to remember:
> - Ensure that the variable is defined in the global scope, outside of functions or blocks.
> - Directly assign the new value without using `var`, `let`, or `const` to avoid declaring a new local variable in the current scope.
